South Africa’s electricity crunch could have many residents looking for backup power systems to provide light in their homes, power their Internet equipment, watch TV, or use certain appliances. MyBroadband looked at some of the cheapest backup power options available — ranging from rechargeable LED light bulbs to petrol-powered generators — to help you through bouts of load-shedding. Eskom implemented Stage 2 load-shedding earlier this week and promptly upped it to Stage 4 two days later. It was reduced to Stage 3 last night. The power utility said the current load-shedding level will remain until 05:00 on Friday, 22 April 2022. Several cost-effective options to get you through bouts of load-shedding are listed below. Several LED light bulbs with a built-in battery backup are available that charge off the mains electricity supply when the power is on. It is important to note that some rechargeable light bulbs require the switch to be turned off and back on to start running off battery power. Manufacturers boast that these can last four to five hours on a full charge. <img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-441598" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/ACDC-emergency-LED-80V.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="533" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/ACDC-emergency-LED-80V.jpg 800w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/ACDC-emergency-LED-80V-600x400.jpg 600w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/ACDC-emergency-LED-80V-768x512.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /> <img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-441602" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/5W-LED-rechargeable-bulb-800V.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="533" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/5W-LED-rechargeable-bulb-800V.jpg 800w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-conte